    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nSome languages (e.g., Rust) suggest that imports should be version-sorted. This more or less corresponds to the `strverscmp` GNU function (https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/strverscmp.3.html) or the behaviour of tools like `ls -v`. This sorting attempts to be a middle ground between pure lexicographical sorting (which would yield `foo1` `foo10` `foo2`...) and sensible sorting of (version) numbers in strings. `strverscmp` does *not* use the LC_COLLATE locale, so it follows the default behaviour of `:sort` (which only uses locale for the `l` flag)\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nA `v` modifier for `:sort` that uses version sorting. This would be mutually exclusive with `l` due to `strverscmp` not using the LC_COLLATE locale as mentioned.\n\n### Upsides\n\n- No reliance on `!sort -V` being available (which, incidentally, uses a slightly different, though unspecified, algorithm from `strverscmp`)\n- Provides a straightforward, plugin-free solution for 'decent' import sorting without needing to set up any external formatters or LSP.\n- Gets to benefit from `:sort v /pat/` for e.g. sorting the output of package management tools or similar.\n\n### Downsides\n\n- GNU libc extension function, thus needs a polyfill for Windows or any non-GNU libc that don't have the function.\n- Might need to be upstreamed to vim first, with the same caveats as above (I don't know if Neovim's core has refactored/rewritten the sort functionality)\n\n### Alternatives\n\n- Stick to external options like `!sort -V`, maybe with a hint in the docs for `:sort`\n- Implement the feature using a different comparison function (which?)\n",
